<DOC><DOCNO> AP880731-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-31-88 2014EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Satellite     07-31 0194</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Satellite,0200</SECOND><HEAD>Indian Communications Satellite Develops Problems</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An Indian communications satellitelaunched 10 days ago from French Guiana has developed a problem inthe power system and scientists are struggling to correct it,United News of India reported Sunday.   It said a solar-powered component malfunctioned Friday.   Indian scientists and a team from Ford Aerospace andCommunications Corp. of Palo Alto, Calif., are working on theproblem, according to the news agency. Ford Aerospace built thesatellite for India.   The Insat-1C satellite was launched on July 22 aboard a EuropeanSpace Agency Ariane-3 rocket from a pad in French Guiana in SouthAmerica and was functioning normally until Friday, the Indian SpaceResearch Organization said.   The 2,618 pound satellite was designed to expand television andlong-distance telephone service in India and collect meteorologicaldata.   UNI said half of the satellite was connected to a power systemthat was operating properly while scientists tried to repair itsmalfunctioning mate.   The problem could represent another setback for India's spaceefforts. On July 13, India failed for a second time to fire intospace its own multistage rocket designed to launch satellites.</TEXT></DOC>